  "prompt": "What traffic laws in Martinique are particularly hard for foreign drivers to get used to?",
  "response": "Foreign drivers in Martinique may encounter several traffic regulations and local driving customs that could be challenging to adjust to:\n\n1. **Roundabouts (Traffic Circles)**: Martinique has numerous roundabouts, and navigating them correctly can be difficult for drivers who are not familiar with yielding rules and general roundabout etiquette. The rule is to give way to traffic coming from the left unless otherwise specified.\n\n2. **Driving Style**: Local driving habits can be more aggressive and fast-paced than in some other countries. This includes frequent lane changes and tailgating.\n\n3. **Priority Rules**: In some areas, especially in rural or residential zones, priority rules can differ from those in other countries. For example, vehicles coming from the right might have priority.\n\n4. **Parking Regulations**: Parking can be tricky, as certain areas may have specific rules such as alternate-side parking or restrictions during certain times. Understanding local signage and regulations is crucial.\n\n5. **Road Conditions**: Martinique has narrow, winding roads, especially in mountainous areas. These roads can be challenging to navigate, particularly for drivers used to wider roads.\n\n6. **Speed Limits**: Speed limits are strictly enforced and can vary widely depending on whether you are on urban roads, rural roads, or highways. Familiarity with these varying limits is essential to avoid fines.\n\n7. **Language Barrier**: Traffic signs and road markings are in French. A basic understanding of common French traffic terms helps in understanding local regulations and directions.\n\n8. **Alcohol Limits**: The legal blood alcohol limit is stricter (0.05%) than in some other countries. Being aware of this and avoiding drinking and driving is crucial.\n\nBeing aware of these factors and taking the time to learn and adapt can help foreign drivers have a safer and more enjoyable driving experience in Martinique.",
